{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515681","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515681"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:33:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12480"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12480"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.67,0.19,0.01,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4987"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110159"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4987"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92457"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8252"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42763"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110159"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old caucasian man presents to his general practitioner for a routine health checkup because he is worried that he might be suffering from diabetes as his elder brother has recently been diagnosed with type 2 diabetes. He is a smoker, and has a history of hypertension for which he is currently taking perindopril. On examination his blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. His BMI is 35kg/m\u00b2. Physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following would be the most appropriate first-line laboratory test to screen for diabetes in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Glycated albumin test","Fasting blood glucose","Random blood glucose test","C-peptide level measurement","Oral glucose tolerance test"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with concerns that he might have diabetes. According to the \u003Ca href=\u0022https://www.health.gov.au/resources/apps-and-tools/the-australian-type-2-diabetes-risk-assessment-tool-ausdrisk\u0022\u003EAUSDRISK assessment score\u003C/a\u003E, he has a score of more than 12, which shows that he has a high risk of developing diabetes mellitus. According to the RACGP guidelines, \u003Cstrong\u003Efasting blood glucose (FBG) \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be the most appropriate diagnostic test for diagnosing diabetes when a patient has a high risk of diabetes mellitus. The results can be categorised into three categories.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u0026lt;5.5 mmol/L (diabetes unlikely).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E5.5\u20136.9 mmol/L (diabetes possible).\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u22657.0 mmol/L (diabetes likely)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBased on these results, the patient is managed further accordingly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eglycated albumin (GA) test\u003C/strong\u003E is typically used as an alternative or complementary test to haemoglobin A1c (HbA1c) in certain clinical situations where HbA1c may be unreliable or inaccurate such as in patients with haemoglobinopathies, anaemia, renal and liver diseases, pregnancy, etc.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHbA1c\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Etest\u003C/strong\u003E which consists of measuring the percentage of glycated haemoglobin and reflects average blood glucose levels over a period of 2-3 months is also an appropriate first-line screening test but may miss early cases of diabetes\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erandom blood glucose test \u003C/strong\u003Eis not an accurate diagnostic test for the diagnosis of diabetes mellitus because blood glucose levels vary considerably throughout the day and it does not give an accurate measurement of the level of glucose in the blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-peptide level measurement\u003C/strong\u003E consists of measuring C-peptide which is a byproduct of insulin synthesis and is released into the bloodstream in equimolar amounts with insulin. A C-peptide level measurement can be helpful in distinguishing between type 1 and type 2 diabetes and assessing insulin secretion. However, it is not the most appropriate diagnostic test for diabetes, as it does not directly measure blood glucose levels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) \u003C/strong\u003Econsists of ingesting a standardised amount of glucose and measuring blood glucose levels at timed intervals. A 2-hour glucose level of 11.1 mmol/L or greater is indicative of diabetes. It is usually not carried out as a first investigation in asymptomatic patients, instead according to the RACGP guidelines, it would be carried out in a patient with FBG levels indicative of possible diabetes (5.5\u20136.9 mmol/L).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A fasting blood glucose test is an appropriate first line test to screen for diabetes mellitus type 2 in asymptomatic high risk patients.","The oral glucose tolerance test is used to confirm diabetes in patients with intermediate fasting blood glucose levels."],"references":["Pippitt K, Li M, Gurgle HE. Diabetes Mellitus: Screening and Diagnosis. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Jan 15;93(2):103-9. Erratum in: Am Fam Physician. 2016 Oct 1;94(7):533. PMID: 26926406. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26926406/","Kaur G, Lakshmi PVM, Rastogi A, Bhansali A, Jain S, Teerawattananon Y, Bano H, Prinja S. Diagnostic accuracy of tests for type 2 diabetes and prediabetes: A systematic review and meta-analysis. PLoS One. 2020 Nov 20;15(11):e0242415. doi: 10.1371/journal.pone.0242415. PMID: 33216783; PMCID: PMC7678987. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33216783/","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Defining and diagnosing type\u202f2 diabetes. In: Management of type\u202f2 diabetes: A handbook for general practice [Internet]. East Melbourne (Vic): RACGP; published November\u202f1\u202f2024 [cited 2025 Jul\u202f28]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/management-of-type-2-diabetes/defining-and-diagnosing-type-2-diabetes"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92457"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12480"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92457"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T16:35:29+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-30T16:48:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4987"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110159"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}